00:00:22.130 --> 00:00:24.230
BENJAMIN BERGEN: So
I'm really thrilled

00:00:24.230 --> 00:00:30.190
to be back in the homeland and
to talk to you about the topic

00:00:30.190 --> 00:00:31.540
of my latest book.

00:00:31.540 --> 00:00:37.500
Now, as Nancy said, there
will be strong language.

00:00:37.500 --> 00:00:39.510
Empirically strong language.

00:00:39.510 --> 00:00:43.820
There will be objectively the
worst words of the language

00:00:43.820 --> 00:00:44.990
on the next slide.

00:00:44.990 --> 00:00:46.970
So this is a great
time-- if you feel

00:00:46.970 --> 00:00:49.820
like you might be uncomfortable
with that sort of thing--

00:00:49.820 --> 00:00:54.280
to conveniently need to slip
out and go get some coffee.

00:00:54.280 --> 00:00:59.700
OK, so human language
serves a variety

00:00:59.700 --> 00:01:01.770
of communicative functions.

00:01:01.770 --> 00:01:04.030
The function that we
usually think about

00:01:04.030 --> 00:01:07.410
is conveying information
through time and space--

00:01:07.410 --> 00:01:09.801
facts, descriptions of things.

00:01:09.801 --> 00:01:11.800
And that's certainly a
thing that language does.

00:01:11.800 --> 00:01:13.300
But it does something
else, as well.

00:01:13.300 --> 00:01:16.000
And that's to convey emotion.

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:19.690
In the hot cognition
of immediate feelings,

00:01:19.690 --> 00:01:23.230
we need some way to
communicate with conspecifics

00:01:23.230 --> 00:01:24.390
that we're angry right now.

00:01:24.390 --> 00:01:26.370
We're frustrated or frightened.

00:01:26.370 --> 00:01:30.310
And this is where
profanity thrives.

00:01:30.310 --> 00:01:33.190
So what I've tried
to do in this book

00:01:33.190 --> 00:01:36.360
is to take an empirical,
cognitive science-based

00:01:36.360 --> 00:01:40.350
approach to what profanity
is, how it works,

00:01:40.350 --> 00:01:42.400
how it comes to be that
way, how it changes over

00:01:42.400 --> 00:01:44.850
time, and importantly,
what it reveals

00:01:44.850 --> 00:01:49.460
about our brains, our
social lives, and ourselves.

00:01:49.460 --> 00:01:52.190
So what I wanted to do
today was to give you

00:01:52.190 --> 00:01:54.890
a brief tour of
some of the things

00:01:54.890 --> 00:01:59.440
that we learn about profanity
and about ourselves,

00:01:59.440 --> 00:02:03.530
our brains, by taking
this leap of faith.

00:02:03.530 --> 00:02:05.970
And to begin with, I
want to start empirically

00:02:05.970 --> 00:02:09.050
by asking what
precisely profanity

00:02:09.050 --> 00:02:10.539
is, where it comes from.

00:02:10.539 --> 00:02:13.100
What words do we
mean by profanity?

00:02:13.100 --> 00:02:15.570
Why are those words profane?

00:02:15.570 --> 00:02:18.060
And if you were to ask
regulatory agencies

00:02:18.060 --> 00:02:21.550
like the FCC, for example,
they wouldn't give you a list.

00:02:21.550 --> 00:02:23.210
Because they haven't
done the legwork.

00:02:23.210 --> 00:02:24.710
They don't actually
know empirically

00:02:24.710 --> 00:02:27.450
what people think is
offensive language.

00:02:27.450 --> 00:02:29.750
But fortunately, we
do have some evidence

00:02:29.750 --> 00:02:33.460
from large-scale
psycholinguistics studies

00:02:33.460 --> 00:02:38.220
that tell us broadly
what the types of words

00:02:38.220 --> 00:02:39.460
are that people find profane.

00:02:39.460 --> 00:02:41.710
And more specifically,
exactly which

00:02:41.710 --> 00:02:43.510
ones a particular
group of people

00:02:43.510 --> 00:02:45.980
find offensive at a
particular time and place.

00:02:45.980 --> 00:02:47.580
So let's start locally.

00:02:47.580 --> 00:02:52.140
Let's start in California with
people in their, say, 20s.

00:02:52.140 --> 00:02:54.990
What are the worst words of
American English according

00:02:54.990 --> 00:02:56.050
to these people?

00:02:56.050 --> 00:02:58.520
So here's a study from
about 10 years ago at UCLA

00:02:58.520 --> 00:03:05.266
that asked undergrads, who
would now be in their mid-20s,

00:03:05.266 --> 00:03:07.030
how would you rate
a list of words

00:03:07.030 --> 00:03:09.830
in terms of their offensiveness,
one word at a time?

00:03:09.830 --> 00:03:12.840
And here are,
without further ado,

00:03:12.840 --> 00:03:15.730
the words that are
worst in English

00:03:15.730 --> 00:03:20.240
according to these respondents
from worst to least bad.

00:03:26.090 --> 00:03:32.040
So some things to note,
for contemporary speakers

00:03:32.040 --> 00:03:35.130
of American English,
including especially younger

00:03:35.130 --> 00:03:37.120
ones, the worst
words in the language

00:03:37.120 --> 00:03:40.420
are predominantly not the
words that George Carlin

00:03:40.420 --> 00:03:42.750
would have told you 50
years ago are the ones you

00:03:42.750 --> 00:03:43.860
can't say on television.

00:03:43.860 --> 00:03:46.580
They're a new class of
words-- slurs, in fact.

00:03:46.580 --> 00:03:52.370
Words that derogate by insulting
a particular social group

00:03:52.370 --> 00:03:54.590
because of their
ethnicity or religion,

00:03:54.590 --> 00:03:56.770
sex, sexual
orientation, and so on.

00:03:56.770 --> 00:03:59.600
And in fact, you find
that a four-letter word

00:03:59.600 --> 00:04:04.210
that starts with f is
actually 13th on the list.

00:04:04.210 --> 00:04:07.550
We can go down the list
if you want and find

00:04:07.550 --> 00:04:11.090
a whole bunch more offensive
words until we get down

00:04:11.090 --> 00:04:14.290
to a famous four-letter word
that starts with S-H that

00:04:14.290 --> 00:04:16.867
doesn't appear to be
that offensive at all

00:04:16.867 --> 00:04:18.950
compared to the rest of
the words in the language.

00:04:18.950 --> 00:04:23.630
Now, when we compare
language taboos

00:04:23.630 --> 00:04:26.100
across the world's
languages, what we discover

00:04:26.100 --> 00:04:30.440
is that the types of words
that feed into this list

00:04:30.440 --> 00:04:33.380
are actually quite
representative of the world's

00:04:33.380 --> 00:04:34.290
languages.

00:04:34.290 --> 00:04:37.490
Across the globe, there
are four categories

00:04:37.490 --> 00:04:40.580
of words that seem to be
most reliable in providing

00:04:40.580 --> 00:04:43.650
the taboo vocabulary
of a language.

00:04:43.650 --> 00:04:48.110
That is words relating to
religious concepts, words

00:04:48.110 --> 00:04:51.860
relating to sex and sexual
activities, words relating

00:04:51.860 --> 00:04:54.980
to other bodily
functions, the organs that

00:04:54.980 --> 00:04:57.100
are responsible for
those functions,

00:04:57.100 --> 00:05:00.150
the actions involved
in those functions,

00:05:00.150 --> 00:05:03.280
the upkeep of those bodily
functions, and so on.

00:05:03.280 --> 00:05:05.630
And then finally, slurs.

00:05:05.630 --> 00:05:08.600
And those are kind of
the big four categories

00:05:08.600 --> 00:05:11.580
that contribute
profane vocabulary.

00:05:11.580 --> 00:05:14.780
And if you were to categorize
the list of most offensive

00:05:14.780 --> 00:05:17.102
words in English by which
of these four categories

00:05:17.102 --> 00:05:18.810
they most properly
belong to-- of course,

00:05:18.810 --> 00:05:21.080
there's a little
bit of wiggle room

00:05:21.080 --> 00:05:26.350
here-- you would find that
in English, it is indeed

00:05:26.350 --> 00:05:29.870
the slurs that, on average
and in specific cases,

00:05:29.870 --> 00:05:32.540
are judged to be the most
profane words of the language,

00:05:32.540 --> 00:05:34.530
the most offensive
words of the language.

00:05:34.530 --> 00:05:39.750
Copulation is also
a near second best.

00:05:39.750 --> 00:05:44.260
And religion doesn't really
provide much profane vocabulary

00:05:44.260 --> 00:05:46.729
to contemporary
American English at all.

00:05:46.729 --> 00:05:48.270
Across the world,
different languages

00:05:48.270 --> 00:05:51.130
will sample differently
from each of these columns.

00:05:51.130 --> 00:05:53.930
So if you look at Italian,
for example, the strongest

00:05:53.930 --> 00:05:57.610
words in Italian
known as bestemmie,

00:05:57.610 --> 00:06:00.670
are basically the
formula is this.

00:06:00.670 --> 00:06:04.475
You take the word pig, and you
add it to a religious term.

00:06:04.475 --> 00:06:06.600
And that gives you a really,
really offensive term.

00:06:06.600 --> 00:06:09.850
So [SPEAKING ITALIAN]
or [SPEAKING ITALIAN],

00:06:09.850 --> 00:06:11.190
really, really offensive.

00:06:11.190 --> 00:06:13.470
Sorry, Italians.

00:06:13.470 --> 00:06:16.590
In Quebecois French,
spoken north of the border,

00:06:16.590 --> 00:06:18.620
the worst words are
these words called

00:06:18.620 --> 00:06:22.120
sacres, which are
Catholic liturgical terms

00:06:22.120 --> 00:06:25.900
like [SPEAKING FRENCH],
or tabernacle,

00:06:25.900 --> 00:06:27.850
or [SPEAKING FRENCH],
which is chalice.

00:06:27.850 --> 00:06:30.430
And these words are far more
offensive than any of the words

00:06:30.430 --> 00:06:34.080
that we have on this list for
speakers of Quebecois French.

00:06:34.080 --> 00:06:37.550
So around the world, languages
will sample differently

00:06:37.550 --> 00:06:41.600
from these groups to find their
most offensive terminology.

00:06:41.600 --> 00:06:46.790
Russian has recently experienced
a big regulatory change.

00:06:46.790 --> 00:06:50.390
Putin's government
has outlawed a set

00:06:50.390 --> 00:06:53.850
of words known as mat, which
are pretty much all drawn

00:06:53.850 --> 00:06:55.720
from sexual vocabulary.

00:06:55.720 --> 00:06:57.970
And those can now no
longer be used in the arts

00:06:57.970 --> 00:07:00.100
or media in general.

00:07:00.100 --> 00:07:02.920
So there are differences
across the world's languages.

00:07:02.920 --> 00:07:06.090
Now, you may be looking
at these words and saying,

00:07:06.090 --> 00:07:09.030
well, OK, this is where
the words come from.

00:07:09.030 --> 00:07:10.730
But there's a lot.

00:07:10.730 --> 00:07:12.270
That can't be sufficient, right?

00:07:12.270 --> 00:07:13.820
There's lots of
words that relate

00:07:13.820 --> 00:07:17.030
to copulation or to bodily
functions that are not obscene,

00:07:17.030 --> 00:07:17.530
right?

00:07:17.530 --> 00:07:19.920
Words that you
would describe when

00:07:19.920 --> 00:07:21.580
talking with a child
in kindergarten,

00:07:21.580 --> 00:07:24.530
or when talking to your
doctor, for example.

00:07:24.530 --> 00:07:28.130
Or when labeling these columns.

00:07:28.130 --> 00:07:31.980
Copulation, for example,
is not a profane word.

00:07:31.980 --> 00:07:34.820
So there must be something
else about the words that

00:07:34.820 --> 00:07:37.480
makes them offensive to people.

00:07:37.480 --> 00:07:40.350
And the first thing that
people oftentimes come up with

00:07:40.350 --> 00:07:42.020
is the length of the word.

00:07:42.020 --> 00:07:44.940
Something about how the word
sounds or how it's spelled.

00:07:44.940 --> 00:07:50.090
We have this idea in English
that there's something special

00:07:50.090 --> 00:07:51.820
about four-letter words, right?

00:07:51.820 --> 00:07:53.744
And in fact, if you
look empirically

00:07:53.744 --> 00:07:55.410
at the distribution
of four-letter words

00:07:55.410 --> 00:07:57.830
among profane words
compared to what

00:07:57.830 --> 00:08:00.410
you'd expect on the basis of
the distribution in the language

00:08:00.410 --> 00:08:02.810
in general, you
do find that there

00:08:02.810 --> 00:08:06.180
are far more profane
four-letter words than you

00:08:06.180 --> 00:08:07.370
would expect by chance.

00:08:07.370 --> 00:08:09.940
And that's true even if you
normalize for the frequency

00:08:09.940 --> 00:08:11.809
of profane words.

00:08:11.809 --> 00:08:13.350
But you find something
else, as well.

00:08:13.350 --> 00:08:15.840
It's not just four-letter
words that are more frequent.

00:08:15.840 --> 00:08:18.271
It's also three-letter
words, and five-letter words,

00:08:18.271 --> 00:08:19.270
and eight- letter words.

00:08:19.270 --> 00:08:21.840
And all those differences
turn out to be significant.

00:08:21.840 --> 00:08:26.190
So what's special about
three-, four-, five-,

00:08:26.190 --> 00:08:27.935
and eight-letter words?

00:08:27.935 --> 00:08:29.810
Well, it has something
to do-- if you go back

00:08:29.810 --> 00:08:32.130
and look at these
words, you can actually

00:08:32.130 --> 00:08:34.100
start to see the pattern.

00:08:34.100 --> 00:08:35.970
The eight-letter
words are made up

00:08:35.970 --> 00:08:38.760
of two four-ish letter words.

00:08:38.760 --> 00:08:41.549
And the four- and five-
and three-letter words

00:08:41.549 --> 00:08:44.300
oftentimes sounds
pretty similar.

00:08:44.300 --> 00:08:46.944
They may be spelled
with five letters,

00:08:46.944 --> 00:08:49.360
but that doesn't mean that
they have five distinct sounds.

00:08:49.360 --> 00:08:52.480
In fact, this is an artifact
of English orthography

00:08:52.480 --> 00:08:54.020
being terrible.

00:08:54.020 --> 00:08:58.160
So English spelling doesn't
look at all like how it sounds.

00:08:58.160 --> 00:09:01.590
It's unlike rational
languages-- like Spanish,

00:09:01.590 --> 00:09:04.970
for example, or Indonesiann--
that actually do have a one

00:09:04.970 --> 00:09:09.190
character per sound dictate.

00:09:09.190 --> 00:09:10.530
Well, in English, not so much.

00:09:10.530 --> 00:09:14.690
And so in fact, what's going
on with these three- and four-

00:09:14.690 --> 00:09:17.240
and five-letter words is
that English profane words

00:09:17.240 --> 00:09:20.250
tend to follow a
particular sound pattern.

00:09:20.250 --> 00:09:23.190
And that sound pattern is this.

00:09:23.190 --> 00:09:26.010
English syllables
come in two varieties.

00:09:26.010 --> 00:09:28.400
There are the ones that
have consonants at the end,

00:09:28.400 --> 00:09:30.460
and the ones that have
no consonants at the end.

00:09:30.460 --> 00:09:32.070
And that makes a big
difference for lots of stuff

00:09:32.070 --> 00:09:33.350
that linguists care about.

00:09:33.350 --> 00:09:36.030
The thing that you should
care about with respect

00:09:36.030 --> 00:09:39.970
to this distinction is
that English profane words

00:09:39.970 --> 00:09:44.850
are far more likely to end with
consonants at the end-- they

00:09:44.850 --> 00:09:47.080
fall into this
category over here--

00:09:47.080 --> 00:09:50.560
than they are to have no
spoken consonants at the end.

00:09:50.560 --> 00:09:54.410
And you could come up with
maybe five words in English

00:09:54.410 --> 00:09:57.650
that are arguably profane
that show up on these lists

00:09:57.650 --> 00:10:01.490
across languages that
people find to be offensive.

00:10:01.490 --> 00:10:05.510
And they're really mostly
not that bad, right?

00:10:05.510 --> 00:10:10.770
So poo is not the strongest
word in the English language.

00:10:10.770 --> 00:10:12.200
Nor is pee, screw.

00:10:12.200 --> 00:10:13.570
Jew shows up on some lists.

00:10:13.570 --> 00:10:16.410
I think it's the use
of Jew as a verb.

00:10:16.410 --> 00:10:18.740
So to Jew someone, or
to Jew someone down

00:10:18.740 --> 00:10:21.300
that is judged to be offensive.

00:10:21.300 --> 00:10:25.070
So there's not a lot of
profane vocabulary in English

00:10:25.070 --> 00:10:27.820
that ends with no consonants.

00:10:27.820 --> 00:10:29.414
Almost all of it
ends with consonants.

00:10:29.414 --> 00:10:31.580
And this differs from the
language in general, which

00:10:31.580 --> 00:10:35.160
is far more evenly balanced
when you look at nouns or verbs

00:10:35.160 --> 00:10:38.480
or frequent words,
infrequent words in general.

00:10:38.480 --> 00:10:40.450
This is a very
strange distribution

00:10:40.450 --> 00:10:41.970
for the sounds of words.

00:10:41.970 --> 00:10:45.320
And so you look at
this distribution.

00:10:45.320 --> 00:10:49.856
And this might start to explain
part of why certain words are

00:10:49.856 --> 00:10:52.480
judged to be more offensive than
others, even though they might

00:10:52.480 --> 00:10:55.920
come from the same
meaning source.

00:10:55.920 --> 00:10:59.240
But is this just a
pattern in the lexicon?

00:10:59.240 --> 00:11:00.730
Is this just a
distributional fact?

00:11:00.730 --> 00:11:02.550
Or is this something
that's actually

00:11:02.550 --> 00:11:04.610
active in the minds
of English speakers?

00:11:04.610 --> 00:11:06.690
Is this something
that you bring to bear

00:11:06.690 --> 00:11:08.480
when you're exposed to a word?

00:11:08.480 --> 00:11:10.740
Do you have this
pattern in mind?

00:11:10.740 --> 00:11:12.700
Does this template
apply to a new word

00:11:12.700 --> 00:11:13.900
that you're exposed to?

00:11:13.900 --> 00:11:16.770
Well, in order to ask this
question, what we did was

00:11:16.770 --> 00:11:20.250
we invented some new words.

00:11:20.250 --> 00:11:23.890
We invented words that didn't
actually exist in English,

00:11:23.890 --> 00:11:27.720
but that were equally
likely to exist

00:11:27.720 --> 00:11:30.310
in English, that had sequences
of sounds or sequences

00:11:30.310 --> 00:11:33.960
of letters that are coherent
with how English works,

00:11:33.960 --> 00:11:35.430
but just don't happen to exist.

00:11:35.430 --> 00:11:43.140
So we made up words like
"ver" and "verd" and "stee"

00:11:43.140 --> 00:11:44.420
and "steet."

00:11:44.420 --> 00:11:46.670
And we asked people to
make various judgments

00:11:46.670 --> 00:11:48.110
about these words.

00:11:48.110 --> 00:11:49.640
How much does it
sound like a word?

00:11:49.640 --> 00:11:51.770
And also, by the
way, how likely do

00:11:51.770 --> 00:11:53.890
you think this word
is to be profane?

00:11:53.890 --> 00:11:55.945
And this is what they said.

00:11:58.460 --> 00:12:01.970
So we had some words that
started with just one consonant

00:12:01.970 --> 00:12:02.770
at the beginning.

00:12:02.770 --> 00:12:03.310
Those are these.

00:12:03.310 --> 00:12:05.420
And then, some that started
with s plus a consonant,

00:12:05.420 --> 00:12:07.560
because that's a nice way
to build more consonants

00:12:07.560 --> 00:12:08.910
into the beginnings of words.

00:12:08.910 --> 00:12:12.410
And so you see two statistically
significant effects here,

00:12:12.410 --> 00:12:13.230
two main effects.

00:12:13.230 --> 00:12:16.790
The first is that if
you have two consonants

00:12:16.790 --> 00:12:19.510
at the beginning, you're going
to be judged more profane.

00:12:19.510 --> 00:12:21.440
That is, higher bars
than if you have only one

00:12:21.440 --> 00:12:22.565
consonant at the beginning.

00:12:22.565 --> 00:12:24.510
These two bars are higher
than these two bars.

00:12:24.510 --> 00:12:26.800
And then, the second effect
is that the dark bars

00:12:26.800 --> 00:12:28.500
are higher than the gray bars.

00:12:28.500 --> 00:12:32.720
And that's showing that if you
have a consonant at the end,

00:12:32.720 --> 00:12:35.510
you're judged to be more profane
than if you have no consonant,

00:12:35.510 --> 00:12:37.160
spoken consonant, at the end.

00:12:37.160 --> 00:12:38.440
And that's true.

00:12:38.440 --> 00:12:41.550
Those two effects are
independent of one another.

00:12:41.550 --> 00:12:44.380
So it appears to
be that people have

00:12:44.380 --> 00:12:46.910
this template in their
minds, this expectation

00:12:46.910 --> 00:12:50.430
that profane words are going
to sound a particular way.

00:12:50.430 --> 00:12:53.190
And when exposed to a brand-new
word, they bring that to bear.

00:12:53.190 --> 00:12:55.890
Now, this is not
particularly surprising

00:12:55.890 --> 00:12:59.180
if you've ever watched
people invent new words.

00:12:59.180 --> 00:13:02.170
So consider the case of fiction.

00:13:02.170 --> 00:13:06.130
So when you have a fictitious
language, say Klingon

00:13:06.130 --> 00:13:09.070
or Dothraki, and
you have to come up

00:13:09.070 --> 00:13:12.660
with what is the profane
inventory going to be like,

00:13:12.660 --> 00:13:14.310
without exception,
English speakers

00:13:14.310 --> 00:13:19.450
make up words that follow this
heavy consonant at the end

00:13:19.450 --> 00:13:21.390
pattern.

00:13:21.390 --> 00:13:24.300
Moreover, when people
invent new profane words--

00:13:24.300 --> 00:13:25.870
and this is happening
all the time--

00:13:25.870 --> 00:13:28.700
those words overwhelmingly
follow this same pattern.

00:13:28.700 --> 00:13:32.710
So I have the privilege of
teaching at UC San Diego, where

00:13:32.710 --> 00:13:35.460
I'm able to consult
on a near daily basis

00:13:35.460 --> 00:13:38.000
with undergraduate students
who are aged 18 to 22.

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:40.030
And they know all kinds
of things about language

00:13:40.030 --> 00:13:42.110
and how it's changing
that I do not know.

00:13:42.110 --> 00:13:44.780
And they bring in new words.

00:13:44.780 --> 00:13:47.220
One of the things that I
ask them is to surprise me,

00:13:47.220 --> 00:13:50.770
tell me something that I don't
know about how people are using

00:13:50.770 --> 00:13:52.730
language in your community.

00:13:52.730 --> 00:13:54.610
And what you find
is that there is

00:13:54.610 --> 00:13:59.490
a whole host of new profane
words with every new crop

00:13:59.490 --> 00:14:00.140
of students.

00:14:00.140 --> 00:14:04.310
So you might not have heard
the word "sperg" before.

00:14:04.310 --> 00:14:05.980
This is a term of
abuse for people

00:14:05.980 --> 00:14:08.070
with Asperger's syndrome.

00:14:08.070 --> 00:14:11.010
You might have heard
the word "tard" before.

00:14:11.010 --> 00:14:13.020
This is an abbreviation
for retard.

00:14:13.020 --> 00:14:15.600
This is judged by
young adults to be

00:14:15.600 --> 00:14:18.500
one of the most offensive words
in the language, more offensive

00:14:18.500 --> 00:14:21.840
than the F word.

00:14:21.840 --> 00:14:24.600
The word MILF, the word
GILF, which is a new one

00:14:24.600 --> 00:14:26.980
that I hadn't heard before.

00:14:26.980 --> 00:14:31.660
So there's a variety of new
words, which, not surprisingly,

00:14:31.660 --> 00:14:34.130
if people have this
pattern in their minds,

00:14:34.130 --> 00:14:39.220
follow this heavy consonant
at the end syllable pattern.

00:14:39.220 --> 00:14:42.060
Now, why do English profanities
tend to sound like this?

00:14:42.060 --> 00:14:44.420
Well, there are a couple
of possible explanations.

00:14:44.420 --> 00:14:46.996
It could be that at some
point in the previous history

00:14:46.996 --> 00:14:48.370
of the language,
it just happened

00:14:48.370 --> 00:14:50.870
to be the case that a
bunch of profane words

00:14:50.870 --> 00:14:52.220
sounded like that.

00:14:52.220 --> 00:14:54.930
And then, over the course
of history, people-- as they

00:14:54.930 --> 00:14:56.630
invented new words--
tended to invent

00:14:56.630 --> 00:14:59.402
words that sounded like
the ones that they already

00:14:59.402 --> 00:15:00.360
knew that were profane.

00:15:00.360 --> 00:15:01.820
They sort of snowballed.

00:15:01.820 --> 00:15:03.890
You had this
accretion by the rich

00:15:03.890 --> 00:15:05.670
getting richer sort of process.

00:15:05.670 --> 00:15:07.180
That's certainly possible.

00:15:07.180 --> 00:15:09.040
But it's also
possible that there's

00:15:09.040 --> 00:15:13.740
some reason to the rhyme,
if you will, that-- that's

00:15:13.740 --> 00:15:20.470
a linguist joke, by the way--
that there's a specific reason

00:15:20.470 --> 00:15:22.470
why this particular pattern.

00:15:22.470 --> 00:15:25.570
Now, when children start
to acquire a language,

00:15:25.570 --> 00:15:28.630
the early sounds that
they're able to produce

00:15:28.630 --> 00:15:33.800
are in conformity
with certain patterns.

00:15:33.800 --> 00:15:35.930
One thing that's very
hard for them to do

00:15:35.930 --> 00:15:38.530
is to produce a bunch of
consonants, especially

00:15:38.530 --> 00:15:40.120
at the end of a syllable.

00:15:40.120 --> 00:15:41.870
Childlike language
tends to reduce

00:15:41.870 --> 00:15:43.980
syllables to just a
consonant and a vowel,

00:15:43.980 --> 00:15:46.240
and often repeats if anything.

00:15:46.240 --> 00:15:49.530
So it's possible
that these words

00:15:49.530 --> 00:15:51.310
are tailored to be
the type of thing that

00:15:51.310 --> 00:15:53.640
sounds least childlike.

00:15:53.640 --> 00:15:56.220
Not because then children
can't produce it, but just

00:15:56.220 --> 00:15:58.780
for the mouthfeel
of the word, it

00:15:58.780 --> 00:16:01.650
feels unlike the type
of thing that a child

00:16:01.650 --> 00:16:02.650
would be likely to say.

00:16:02.650 --> 00:16:05.190
And it also sounds
unlikely to be something

00:16:05.190 --> 00:16:06.870
that a child would say.

00:16:06.870 --> 00:16:09.450
A final possibility is that
it might have something

00:16:09.450 --> 00:16:12.930
to do with the use that
you put these words to.

00:16:12.930 --> 00:16:15.090
And I first started
thinking about this

00:16:15.090 --> 00:16:18.150
when I saw interviews with
people with Tourette syndrome.

00:16:18.150 --> 00:16:20.440
Now, you may or may not
be familiar with Tourette

00:16:20.440 --> 00:16:21.000
syndrome.

00:16:21.000 --> 00:16:24.080
It's an inhibitory
control disorder where--

00:16:24.080 --> 00:16:25.770
it's a developmental disorder.

00:16:25.770 --> 00:16:28.740
People have trouble
controlling tics,

00:16:28.740 --> 00:16:32.000
which are movements usually of
the head and neck, sometimes

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:32.900
the upper torso.

00:16:32.900 --> 00:16:37.300
About 10% of the time, they
also have a particular symptom

00:16:37.300 --> 00:16:41.000
known as coprolalia, which is
the uncontrollable production

00:16:41.000 --> 00:16:42.750
of taboo words.

00:16:42.750 --> 00:16:45.730
And it so happens that
when you ask people

00:16:45.730 --> 00:16:48.430
how they control
this coprolalia,

00:16:48.430 --> 00:16:51.270
they often report
that what they do

00:16:51.270 --> 00:16:54.610
is they can't control the
beginning of the word.

00:16:54.610 --> 00:16:56.860
So one person I saw
interviewed, for example,

00:16:56.860 --> 00:16:58.940
said that his tic
was the word "cock."

00:16:58.940 --> 00:17:01.217
So he couldn't
not say that word.

00:17:01.217 --> 00:17:02.050
He would be at work.

00:17:02.050 --> 00:17:02.966
He would be in public.

00:17:02.966 --> 00:17:04.890
He'd be at a ball
game with his kids,

00:17:04.890 --> 00:17:07.490
and he just couldn't
not say that word.

00:17:07.490 --> 00:17:10.690
But he could change
the end of the word.

00:17:10.690 --> 00:17:13.470
He could just close his mouth.

00:17:13.470 --> 00:17:15.339
So "cop," and so
his solution was

00:17:15.339 --> 00:17:17.250
to say "cop," cop,
cop, cop, cop.

00:17:17.250 --> 00:17:20.876
And he described the effect
as being that people thought

00:17:20.876 --> 00:17:22.250
that he was a
little bit strange,

00:17:22.250 --> 00:17:24.900
but certainly it didn't
have the consequence of him

00:17:24.900 --> 00:17:27.319
not being able to go
out in public anymore.

00:17:27.319 --> 00:17:31.180
And so it occurs to me
that one of the things

00:17:31.180 --> 00:17:33.990
that having a bunch of
consonants at the end does

00:17:33.990 --> 00:17:35.060
is it stops the word.

00:17:35.060 --> 00:17:37.390
So if what you want
to do with profanity

00:17:37.390 --> 00:17:39.530
is to express a strong
emotion and then

00:17:39.530 --> 00:17:44.249
be able to quickly curtail the
audibleness of that expression,

00:17:44.249 --> 00:17:45.790
then maybe it would
be useful to have

00:17:45.790 --> 00:17:48.164
something at the end that's
not a vowel, but a consonant.

00:17:48.164 --> 00:17:50.790
And there's a little bit
of corroborating evidence

00:17:50.790 --> 00:17:51.700
for this.

00:17:51.700 --> 00:17:54.450
The consonants that you can
stick at the end of a word

00:17:54.450 --> 00:17:57.690
are not all equal in their
ability to stop sound.

00:17:57.690 --> 00:17:59.730
There are some called
stop consonants,

00:17:59.730 --> 00:18:02.380
like puh, and tuh, and
kuh, that really do just

00:18:02.380 --> 00:18:04.660
stop the sound coming
out of your mouth.

00:18:04.660 --> 00:18:06.590
And if those are
the ones that are

00:18:06.590 --> 00:18:09.040
most likely to occur at
the ends of profane words,

00:18:09.040 --> 00:18:11.190
then this is consistent
with that explanation.

00:18:11.190 --> 00:18:15.380
And in fact, if you count all
English monosyllabic words,

00:18:15.380 --> 00:18:18.360
and you look at the
ending consonants,

00:18:18.360 --> 00:18:20.910
there are about as many stop
consonants, like puh, tuh, kuh,

00:18:20.910 --> 00:18:22.354
as there are nonstop consonants.

00:18:22.354 --> 00:18:23.770
That's in the
language in general.

00:18:23.770 --> 00:18:26.980
But if you look just at profane
English monosyllabic words,

00:18:26.980 --> 00:18:29.320
there are far more stops
than nonstop consonants.

00:18:33.270 --> 00:18:34.060
So that's a thing.

00:18:34.060 --> 00:18:36.580
Anyway, as you look
across languages,

00:18:36.580 --> 00:18:40.521
you find that this sound pattern
doesn't necessarily hold up.

00:18:40.521 --> 00:18:42.020
So there are
languages, for example,

00:18:42.020 --> 00:18:46.180
that just don't allow consonants
at the ends of syllables.

00:18:46.180 --> 00:18:48.140
So Japanese mostly
doesn't allow consonants

00:18:48.140 --> 00:18:51.146
at the ends of syllables
except for "n," but no others.

00:18:51.146 --> 00:18:52.770
Hawaiian mostly
doesn't like consonants

00:18:52.770 --> 00:18:53.990
at the ends of syllables.

00:18:53.990 --> 00:18:56.080
So in those languages,
you just couldn't have it.

00:18:56.080 --> 00:19:00.740
If you turn-- well, I'm in San
Diego, so if you turn south,

00:19:00.740 --> 00:19:02.490
you find that Spanish
doesn't really

00:19:02.490 --> 00:19:04.080
have this pattern, either.

00:19:04.080 --> 00:19:08.120
Most words in Spanish
that are nouns or verbs,

00:19:08.120 --> 00:19:11.570
adjectives, adverbs are
multi-syllable words.

00:19:11.570 --> 00:19:13.870
So you don't really get
one-syllable profanity

00:19:13.870 --> 00:19:14.370
in Spanish.

00:19:14.370 --> 00:19:15.786
So there are
certainly differences

00:19:15.786 --> 00:19:17.540
across the world's languages.

00:19:17.540 --> 00:19:19.150
So more to be explored here.

00:19:19.150 --> 00:19:23.540
But you certainly see that
across the world's languages,

00:19:23.540 --> 00:19:26.980
there is a tendency to have
something like profanity drawn

00:19:26.980 --> 00:19:29.180
from one of these
four categories,

00:19:29.180 --> 00:19:31.530
having certain sound
patterns, although maybe not

00:19:31.530 --> 00:19:33.290
these specific sound patterns.

00:19:33.290 --> 00:19:37.180
And there are few exceptions to
the fact of having profanity.

00:19:37.180 --> 00:19:38.860
But there are exceptions.

00:19:38.860 --> 00:19:42.280
So in some languages, or in
some cultures, I should say,

00:19:42.280 --> 00:19:43.720
there's not even a setting.

00:19:43.720 --> 00:19:45.890
There's not even a
pervasive cultural belief

00:19:45.890 --> 00:19:47.990
that there's a set
of words that we all

00:19:47.990 --> 00:19:51.510
agree are the bad words that
we shouldn't say in public,

00:19:51.510 --> 00:19:54.100
we shouldn't say around kids,
we shouldn't allow kids to say,

00:19:54.100 --> 00:19:57.536
that need to be bleeped, that
people should be punished for.

00:19:57.536 --> 00:19:59.160
So for example, it's
long been reported

00:19:59.160 --> 00:20:01.040
that this is the case in Japan.

00:20:01.040 --> 00:20:05.220
So there isn't this
sort of social setting

00:20:05.220 --> 00:20:09.740
that there is a set of words
that we need to make sure

00:20:09.740 --> 00:20:11.940
that kids are protected from.

00:20:11.940 --> 00:20:16.784
So there are lots of ways to
insult people in Japanese.

00:20:16.784 --> 00:20:18.950
There are lots of ways to
offend people in Japanese.

00:20:18.950 --> 00:20:21.110
You can insult
people's ancestors

00:20:21.110 --> 00:20:22.560
and liken them to animals.

00:20:22.560 --> 00:20:24.190
That is a really
offensive thing to do.

00:20:24.190 --> 00:20:26.650
You can call people ignorant.

00:20:26.650 --> 00:20:31.190
You can use the wrong honorific
forms, those little endings

00:20:31.190 --> 00:20:32.965
on the ends of
verbs and nouns that

00:20:32.965 --> 00:20:35.340
make it seem like you're
talking to someone of low status

00:20:35.340 --> 00:20:37.530
rather than high status.

00:20:37.530 --> 00:20:42.140
But specific words that
are bad words, not so much.

00:20:42.140 --> 00:20:44.340
If you want to say that
someone's-- if you want

00:20:44.340 --> 00:20:47.640
to insult someone, you
might use the word baka.

00:20:47.640 --> 00:20:50.800
To talk about genitalia,
you might use chinchin.

00:20:50.800 --> 00:20:54.721
Some people say that kuso,
which literally means excrement,

00:20:54.721 --> 00:20:57.220
is the closest thing that there
is to profanity in Japanese.

00:20:57.220 --> 00:20:59.660
But you see it in
Hello Kitty videos.

00:20:59.660 --> 00:21:03.410
I mean, it clearly
doesn't rise to the level

00:21:03.410 --> 00:21:08.810
of even "shit," which as we
saw, doesn't break the top 30.

00:21:08.810 --> 00:21:14.480
So across the world's
languages, the idea of profanity

00:21:14.480 --> 00:21:17.480
is actually built off of
something a little bit more

00:21:17.480 --> 00:21:21.750
than just having words
belonging to certain domains

00:21:21.750 --> 00:21:22.930
of experience.

00:21:22.930 --> 00:21:25.952
And more than just having
words that sound powerful,

00:21:25.952 --> 00:21:26.910
there's something else.

00:21:26.910 --> 00:21:28.810
There's a cultural setting.

00:21:28.810 --> 00:21:31.800
And what we find when we look
within a culture across time

00:21:31.800 --> 00:21:33.580
is that you get the
exact same effect.

00:21:33.580 --> 00:21:35.860
That over the course
of the history

00:21:35.860 --> 00:21:39.830
of a language, a particular word
may enter into being profane.

00:21:39.830 --> 00:21:44.670
And then decades or centuries
later may no longer be profane.

00:21:44.670 --> 00:21:48.620
So it just so happens that if
you know someone named Dick,

00:21:48.620 --> 00:21:51.360
he's probably 65
years old or older.

00:21:51.360 --> 00:21:53.990
And the reason I know
that is that I went and I

00:21:53.990 --> 00:21:56.490
dug into the Social Security
Administration naming

00:21:56.490 --> 00:22:01.940
database, which has
records of every live birth

00:22:01.940 --> 00:22:03.840
recorded in the United States.

00:22:03.840 --> 00:22:07.060
And as it turned out, there
was a long period of US history

00:22:07.060 --> 00:22:11.171
in which children were being
given the given name Dick.

00:22:11.171 --> 00:22:12.670
Not Richard-- these
weren't Richards

00:22:12.670 --> 00:22:13.520
who were nicknamed Dick.

00:22:13.520 --> 00:22:14.790
They were actually named Dick.

00:22:14.790 --> 00:22:16.870
It said "Dick" on their
birth certificate.

00:22:16.870 --> 00:22:19.030
So what I did was I
just counted over,

00:22:19.030 --> 00:22:21.830
on a year by year basis,
how many Dicks there were

00:22:21.830 --> 00:22:25.050
and how many Ricks there were.

00:22:25.050 --> 00:22:27.780
And here's the data.

00:22:27.780 --> 00:22:30.670
It sort of speaks for itself.

00:22:30.670 --> 00:22:34.730
There was a time when
there were lots of Dicks.

00:22:34.730 --> 00:22:41.630
And then, by 1965, there
were no more Dicks.

00:22:41.630 --> 00:22:45.050
There were Ricks and there were
Richards, but no more Dicks.

00:22:45.050 --> 00:22:48.240
And I actually have
a relative named

00:22:48.240 --> 00:22:52.530
Richard who was born
right around here

00:22:52.530 --> 00:22:54.830
who went by Dick
until the mid-1990s.

00:22:54.830 --> 00:22:56.870
And then, we got an
email saying, by the way,

00:22:56.870 --> 00:22:58.000
I'm now going by Rick.

00:22:58.000 --> 00:23:00.990
And this is a totally
rational thing to do.

00:23:00.990 --> 00:23:01.900
For obvious reasons.

00:23:01.900 --> 00:23:06.630
This is a word that had
accumulated enough impact

00:23:06.630 --> 00:23:09.480
in its secondary meaning, its
new, acquired meaning, which

00:23:09.480 --> 00:23:12.130
interestingly seems to
have arisen indirectly

00:23:12.130 --> 00:23:15.430
from a meaning relating
to-- so "dick" first

00:23:15.430 --> 00:23:19.630
came to mean a riding crop, like
the handle of a riding crop.

00:23:19.630 --> 00:23:22.010
You can see how it then would
be metaphorically extended

00:23:22.010 --> 00:23:26.210
to a body part that was
maybe shaped similarly.

00:23:26.210 --> 00:23:29.910
But that change took
decades to take effect,

00:23:29.910 --> 00:23:32.130
to the point where
people started

00:23:32.130 --> 00:23:35.930
to decide that other meaning
is just too invasive.

00:23:35.930 --> 00:23:38.830
It's just too problematic
when I introduce myself.

00:23:38.830 --> 00:23:40.810
And we see this
not just with Dick,

00:23:40.810 --> 00:23:42.680
but you can plot
the same history

00:23:42.680 --> 00:23:45.350
with a closely
related word, "cock,"

00:23:45.350 --> 00:23:50.700
which used to only
refer to the rooster

00:23:50.700 --> 00:23:52.635
before the word
"rooster" existed.

00:23:52.635 --> 00:23:54.640
It then gained a
secondary meaning.

00:23:54.640 --> 00:23:56.940
It gained a meaning
relating to, well, actually

00:23:56.940 --> 00:23:58.360
the same thing that "dick" did.

00:23:58.360 --> 00:24:02.900
And at that point, after
some centuries of discomfort,

00:24:02.900 --> 00:24:05.460
Puritanical Americans
in the 18th century

00:24:05.460 --> 00:24:08.070
decided this was not a
stable state of affairs.

00:24:08.070 --> 00:24:12.030
And they really needed another
way to describe, to call,

00:24:12.030 --> 00:24:13.540
the male of the chicken.

00:24:13.540 --> 00:24:16.120
And they invented a
word based on the place

00:24:16.120 --> 00:24:18.350
that that animal sleeps.

00:24:18.350 --> 00:24:20.930
It sleeps in a roost,
so it is a rooster.

00:24:20.930 --> 00:24:27.684
And that word gained familiarity
and use in the United States,

00:24:27.684 --> 00:24:30.100
although it hasn't caught on
in other places in the world.

00:24:30.100 --> 00:24:32.110
So you still have, for
example, Great Britain

00:24:32.110 --> 00:24:34.276
where "rooster" is sort
of a funny American word

00:24:34.276 --> 00:24:35.150
that they know about.

00:24:35.150 --> 00:24:38.080
Kind of like how like
a lorry is for us.

00:24:38.080 --> 00:24:41.510
It's like, ha, whatever,
you guys are ridiculous.

00:24:41.510 --> 00:24:42.780
It was kind of the same thing.

00:24:42.780 --> 00:24:46.270
So what we see across words when
we look at profane vocabulary

00:24:46.270 --> 00:24:48.040
is that they follow
this pattern.

00:24:48.040 --> 00:24:50.210
That at first, they're
not profane at all.

00:24:50.210 --> 00:24:52.350
Refer to animals or to people.

00:24:52.350 --> 00:24:54.270
That they gain profane meanings.

00:24:54.270 --> 00:24:58.660
That those profane meanings
squeeze out the old meanings,

00:24:58.660 --> 00:25:02.510
create an externality of having
to invent new words to cover

00:25:02.510 --> 00:25:05.180
the semantic ground that
is now no longer covered

00:25:05.180 --> 00:25:08.410
by the word that's not being
used in its original way.

00:25:08.410 --> 00:25:11.840
And then, eventually,
these words die out.

00:25:11.840 --> 00:25:14.680
So many of the most
profane words from English

00:25:14.680 --> 00:25:16.690
are no longer used.

00:25:16.690 --> 00:25:19.140
So if I were to tell you
that in Shakespeare's time

00:25:19.140 --> 00:25:22.610
the equivalent of the
F word was "swive,"

00:25:22.610 --> 00:25:25.550
you would only know that if you
were a Shakespearean scholar.

00:25:25.550 --> 00:25:27.930
It comes from an old
root meaning something

00:25:27.930 --> 00:25:30.580
like to turn or screw.

00:25:30.580 --> 00:25:32.630
We have other words
that have followed

00:25:32.630 --> 00:25:34.660
a similar semantic pattern.

00:25:34.660 --> 00:25:37.910
But it has completely
fallen out of use.

00:25:37.910 --> 00:25:42.780
So has "tarnation," and so
has "gadzooks," and "zounds."

00:25:42.780 --> 00:25:44.800
These are all words
that, at some point,

00:25:44.800 --> 00:25:47.350
were extremely vulgar.

00:25:47.350 --> 00:25:49.460
"Gadzooks" comes
from "God's eyes,"

00:25:49.460 --> 00:25:52.440
and it falls into this
religious terminology,

00:25:52.440 --> 00:25:53.880
but no longer is used at all.

00:25:53.880 --> 00:25:56.650
And so this is the general
pattern that we observe.

00:25:56.650 --> 00:25:59.950
If we are to project
forward, we can reasonably

00:25:59.950 --> 00:26:01.920
assume that the very set
of words that are now

00:26:01.920 --> 00:26:04.580
judged to be the most offensive
ones in the English language,

00:26:04.580 --> 00:26:07.309
within a century
certainly, will no longer

00:26:07.309 --> 00:26:08.600
have the impact that they have.

00:26:08.600 --> 00:26:11.260
And it would be surprising
if the F word, for example,

00:26:11.260 --> 00:26:16.190
were still censored on broadcast
television in 20 years.

00:26:16.190 --> 00:26:19.370
But at the point at which
there is some ambiguity,

00:26:19.370 --> 00:26:22.310
there's ample opportunity
for double entendre.

00:26:22.310 --> 00:26:24.620
And so just because this
is a real thing that

00:26:24.620 --> 00:26:26.360
actually happened, I
wanted to show this.

00:26:26.360 --> 00:26:29.020
So right around
here in the 1960s,

00:26:29.020 --> 00:26:31.800
there was a very famous
person whose name was Richard.

00:26:31.800 --> 00:26:35.340
And his proponents played
on this double meaning

00:26:35.340 --> 00:26:39.940
to create this actual,
real political messaging.

00:26:46.464 --> 00:26:48.380
It's the type of thing
that you could get away

00:26:48.380 --> 00:26:53.790
with in 1955 or 1965
because there was still--

00:26:53.790 --> 00:26:56.790
because his name
was Dick, right?

00:26:56.790 --> 00:26:59.994
Maybe not the thing that you
could get away with in 2016.

00:26:59.994 --> 00:27:01.160
Or maybe actually you could.

00:27:01.160 --> 00:27:03.057
I guess we'll find out
in about three weeks.

00:27:06.040 --> 00:27:08.200
OK, so what makes profanity?

00:27:08.200 --> 00:27:11.215
Well, there's a whole bunch
that goes into making profanity.

00:27:11.215 --> 00:27:13.300
First, you have to
have a cultural belief

00:27:13.300 --> 00:27:15.040
that some words are bad.

00:27:15.040 --> 00:27:16.550
And you don't have to have that.

00:27:16.550 --> 00:27:20.430
You could be Japanese and not
have that cultural belief.

00:27:20.430 --> 00:27:23.550
Second, you have to apply that
belief to specific words, which

00:27:23.550 --> 00:27:26.290
are most likely to be drawn from
certain categories of meaning.

00:27:26.290 --> 00:27:28.580
And they make a pattern
together in sound.

00:27:28.580 --> 00:27:31.670
And then, in order
for that belief system

00:27:31.670 --> 00:27:35.250
to be inserted into
people's brains,

00:27:35.250 --> 00:27:37.950
there has to be some
system for reinforcing it.

00:27:37.950 --> 00:27:41.910
So there has to be some system
of punishment, censorship.

00:27:41.910 --> 00:27:44.210
Ironically, the
punishment-- the soap

00:27:44.210 --> 00:27:47.120
in the mouth, the bleeping
on television-- that

00:27:47.120 --> 00:27:50.500
is exactly what makes
those specific words

00:27:50.500 --> 00:27:52.050
have the taboos that they have.

00:27:52.050 --> 00:27:54.570
It is the thing that
recreates that belief

00:27:54.570 --> 00:27:59.470
system for each new generation
of speakers of the language.

00:27:59.470 --> 00:28:03.440
Now, I wanted to talk to you
not just about what profanity is

00:28:03.440 --> 00:28:06.480
and some of the science
of what we know about it,

00:28:06.480 --> 00:28:10.810
but also what it uniquely
reveals about our brains.

00:28:10.810 --> 00:28:13.000
And so that's what I
wanted to turn to next.

00:28:13.000 --> 00:28:15.450
There are certain
facts about how

00:28:15.450 --> 00:28:20.210
profanity is used that differ
from the rest of language.

00:28:20.210 --> 00:28:22.070
Profanity is emotional.

00:28:22.070 --> 00:28:24.280
It evokes emotions
in other people.

00:28:24.280 --> 00:28:26.329
It is inhibited.

00:28:26.329 --> 00:28:27.870
It is the type of
thing that you know

00:28:27.870 --> 00:28:30.150
you're not supposed to say
in certain circumstances.

00:28:30.150 --> 00:28:33.597
And as a consequence, it
uses different brain systems

00:28:33.597 --> 00:28:34.680
from the rest of language.

00:28:34.680 --> 00:28:37.130
And I'm going to show you
now two kinds of things

00:28:37.130 --> 00:28:40.660
that we learn about how
our brains compute language

00:28:40.660 --> 00:28:45.060
on the basis of
this side effect.

00:28:45.060 --> 00:28:47.220
So the first has to
do with speech errors.

00:28:47.220 --> 00:28:49.180
Speech is peppered with errors.

00:28:49.180 --> 00:28:51.010
I've tried to not
produce many now.

00:28:51.010 --> 00:28:53.490
But in fact, people produce
roughly an error every thousand

00:28:53.490 --> 00:28:54.330
words.

00:28:54.330 --> 00:28:55.800
It's a lot.

00:28:55.800 --> 00:28:59.070
In particular, it's been
believed for a long time

00:28:59.070 --> 00:29:01.890
that the speech errors
may reflect thoughts

00:29:01.890 --> 00:29:04.140
that people have that
they are not consciously--

00:29:04.140 --> 00:29:06.530
or that they are consciously
trying to suppress.

00:29:06.530 --> 00:29:08.810
And if this is
true, then we might

00:29:08.810 --> 00:29:13.110
expect to find that
repressed thoughts produce

00:29:13.110 --> 00:29:18.430
more taboo errors than non-taboo
errors, all things being equal.

00:29:18.430 --> 00:29:21.490
And certainly, we tend to
notice when people make

00:29:21.490 --> 00:29:24.650
speech errors that are vulgar.

